<h2><a name="Short_Writing_Assignment"></a> Short Writing Assignment </h2>
 <blockquote> <strong>Due by 11:59 p.m. Wed., September 12, 2012</strong> </blockquote>
Write a short essay (roughly 300 words) about some topic related to computing technology or the Internet that interest you and has social or ethical implications. Describe the background; then identify the issues, problems, or questions that you think are important.
<p />
Submit this essay via the appropriate discussion discussion board in Blackboard. <span style="color: #ff0000"> <strong>You must attach the file containing your essay AND paste the text of your essay in the message of your post!</strong> </span>
<h2><a name="Major_Assignments_Book_Report_Te"></a> Major Assignments: Book Report &amp; Term Paper </h2> <ul>
<li> <a href="/bin/view/CS335/BookReport" class="twikiLink">BookReport</a>
</li> <li> <a href="/bin/view/CS335/TermPaper" class="twikiLink">TermPaper</a>
</li></ul> 
<h2><a name="Small_Assignment_Sending_encrypt"></a> Small Assignment:Sending encrypted email with S/MIME </h2>
 Please follow these steps.  <ol>
<li> Get yourself a certificate. mozillaZine has a <a href="http://kb.mozillazine.org/Getting_an_SMIME_certificate" target="_top">list of providers of free S/MIME certificates</a>. I suggest you use one of the sources that offers more than a 30&ndash;60 day trial, and please do not use the source that called out as not being a built-in trusted source for Mozilla or Thunderbird.
</li> <li> Install the certificate in the mail client of your choice (e.g., Thunderbird, Outlook, Outlook Express, Apple Mail.app).  <ul>
<li> Alternate method: You can try using the plugin for GMail webmail under Firefox. I've read conflicting things about whether it is working for the current version of Firefox (FF 4).
</li></ul> 
</li> <li> Send a singed but not encrypted email to Prof. Sloan's UIC email address.
</li> <li> Prof. Sloan will email right back to you with something signed and encrypted.
</li> <li> Then send a encrypted (and signed) email to Prof. Sloan's UIC email address.
</li></ol> 
(The reason for the back and forth is that that way our email software will automagically acquire each other's keys.)
<p />
-- Main.troy - 2012-08-24 </div><!-- /patternTopic-->
